```jsx
import React, { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { StyleSheet, Text, View } from 'react-native';
import axios from 'axios';

const App = () => {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchData();
  }, []);

  async function fetchData() {
    const result = await axios('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1');
    setData(result.data);
  }

  return (
      <View style={styles.container}>
        <Text>Sample Template</Text>
        {!data && <Text>Loading...</Text>}
        {data && (
          <>
            <Text>{`Task Title: ${data.title}`}</Text>
            <Text>{`Status: ${data.completed ? "Completed" : "Not Completed"}`}</Text>
          </>
        )}
      </View>
   );
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  container: {
    flex:1,
    backgroundColor:'#fff',
    alignItems:'center',
    justifyContent:'center'
   },
});

export default App;
```

This code is doing the following things:

- It imports necessary modules at the beginning.
- It declares a functional component called `App`.
- Inside `App`, it sets up a piece of state with `useState` to hold our data that we'll fetch in a bit.
- Then it uses the `useEffect` hook to trigger our fetch request as soon as our component mounts.
- The fetching itself is done through the asynchronous function `fetchData`. This one uses Axios to perform GET requests but you could just as easily use Fetch or another http client.
- In case nothing was fetched yet (maybe because it's loading), display Loading text.

